		<div id="comment-469151">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/51042462c6b3d20f5e7ca4eeb1807986?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/51042462c6b3d20f5e7ca4eeb1807986?s=80&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://kevin-standlee.livejournal.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Kevin</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-469151">
				January 14, 2016 at 14:05					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>See our discussion of the <a href="../../../index.html?page_id=3" rel="nofollow">Hugo Award categories</a> for more information. Novellas are works between 17,500 and 40,000 words long. Novelettes are works between 7,500 and 17,500 words long.</p>
<p>You cannot &#8220;submit&#8221; a work for consideration. See <a href="../../../index.html?page_id=191" rel="nofollow">Submitting Your Work</a> for more information.</p>
<p>There is no list of &#8220;approved publishers.&#8221; It doesn&#8217;t matter who publishes the work. All works of SF/F in any format from any publisher (including self-published works) are eligible for the Hugo Awards.</p>
<p>It does not matter if the work of SF/F was published in a collection of other works that was not SF/F.</p>
</div>

				<div class="reply">
